<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Is thalassotherapy scientifically proven to work?</h3>
<p>Thalassotherapy has a growing body of clinical evidence supporting its use for several conditions, particularly arthritis, chronic pain, psoriasis, and respiratory issues. Multiple randomized controlled trials have found statistically significant improvements compared to control groups. However, the overall evidence base is smaller than for mainstream medical treatments, and many studies have methodological limitations (such as difficulty blinding participants). The scientific consensus is that thalassotherapy can be a valuable complementary therapy when used alongside conventional medical treatment, but it should not be relied upon as a sole treatment for serious medical conditions.</p>

<h3>How is thalassotherapy different from just swimming in the sea?</h3>
<p>While sea swimming provides many of the same mineral-exposure benefits as thalassotherapy, clinical thalassotherapy differs in several important ways. First, the seawater in thalassotherapy centres is heated to specific therapeutic temperatures (typically 33–36°C), which promotes vasodilation, muscle relaxation, and mineral absorption far more effectively than cold sea swimming. Second, the seawater is filtered to remove biological contaminants while retaining minerals. Third, treatments are administered under professional supervision using specific protocols, durations, and complementary therapies (algae wraps, mud treatments, jet massage) designed to maximize therapeutic outcomes. Finally, the controlled environment allows treatment year-round, regardless of weather or sea conditions.</p>

<h3>How many thalassotherapy sessions do I need to see results?</h3>
<p>For general relaxation and wellness, even a single session can produce noticeable benefits — reduced muscle tension, improved skin condition, and a sense of deep relaxation. For therapeutic purposes (managing a chronic condition), most thalassotherapy practitioners recommend a minimum of 3–5 consecutive days of treatment for initial results, with periodic "maintenance" sessions thereafter. Clinical studies that demonstrated significant benefits for conditions like arthritis and fibromyalgia typically used treatment programmes lasting 1–3 weeks. Many people who discover thalassotherapy incorporate it as a regular part of their wellness routine, returning for periodic courses throughout the year.</p>

<h3>Can children undergo thalassotherapy?</h3>
<p>Some thalassotherapy treatments are suitable for children, but with modifications. Warm seawater pool immersion at moderate temperatures is generally safe for children over the age of 3, provided they are supervised by a parent and the pool temperature does not exceed 34°C. However, saunas, steam rooms, intense hydromassage jets, and treatments involving concentrated algae or mud products are generally not recommended for young children. Marine aerosol therapy (inhaling seawater mist) is sometimes used for children with respiratory conditions such as asthma or chronic sinusitis, but this should be done under medical supervision. Always consult a pediatrician before any thalassotherapy treatment for a child.</p>

<h3>Is the Mediterranean Sea clean enough for thalassotherapy in Mallorca?</h3>
<p>Mallorca''s coastal waters are among the cleanest in the Mediterranean, with the vast majority of the island''s beaches holding Blue Flag or similar quality certifications. The Balearic Islands benefit from strong environmental protection regulations, relatively low levels of industrial pollution, and excellent waste water treatment infrastructure. Professional thalassotherapy centres like the Elba Sunset pump seawater from optimal locations and filter it to clinical standards before use, ensuring that the water used in treatments meets strict hygiene requirements. For natural sea swimming, Mallorca''s water quality is regularly tested by the Balearic Islands government and the European Environment Agency, with results publicly available.</p>

<h3>Can thalassotherapy help with weight loss?</h3>
<p>Thalassotherapy is not a weight loss treatment per se, and any claims of significant fat reduction from seawater immersion alone should be viewed with scepticism. However, thalassotherapy may support a weight management programme in several indirect ways: warm seawater exercise burns calories while being gentler on joints than land-based exercise (ideal for overweight individuals); algae wraps may temporarily reduce the appearance of water retention; the magnesium in seawater can improve sleep quality, which is linked to healthier weight management; and the stress-reducing effects of thalassotherapy can help combat stress-related eating. Some thalassotherapy centres offer weight management programmes that combine seawater treatments with nutritional counselling and guided exercise.</p>

<h3>What should I bring to a thalassotherapy session?</h3>
<p>Most thalassotherapy centres provide robes, towels, and slippers. You should bring a swimsuit (required for pool areas), flip-flops or waterproof sandals, a change of underwear, basic toiletries, a water bottle (hydration is essential), and any medical information relevant to your treatment (medication list, doctor''s notes for specific conditions). Avoid wearing jewellery, as the minerals in seawater can tarnish metals. If you wear contact lenses, consider switching to glasses for your visit, as the salt and mineral content of the water can irritate eyes if splashed. Arrive without heavy makeup or perfume, as these can interfere with treatments and contaminate pool water.</p>

<h3>Is thalassotherapy covered by health insurance in Spain?</h3>
<p>In Spain, thalassotherapy is generally not covered by public health insurance (Seguridad Social) or standard private health insurance policies. However, some private insurance plans that include wellness or complementary therapy benefits may partially cover thalassotherapy treatments prescribed by a doctor for specific medical conditions. In France, certain thalassotherapy programmes prescribed by a physician are partially reimbursed by social security — a model that Spain has not yet adopted. If you have private health insurance, check your policy for coverage of "hydrotherapy," "balneotherapy," or "complementary therapies," as thalassotherapy may fall under these categories.</p>

